We start by extracting the key figures from the three statements.

1. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 • Total Liabilities are found as the “Total Current Liabilities”, which is 499,821.72.  
 • Total Owner’s Equity is 14,390,936.99.  
 • Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 499,821.72 / 14,390,936.99 ≈ 0.0347  
  Rounded, we report this as 0.03.

2. Net Profit Margin  
 • Net Profit from the income statement is 1,390,936.99.  
 • Total Revenue is 3,956,433.90.  
 • Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%  
  = (1,390,936.99 / 3,956,433.90) × 100% ≈ 35.17%

3. Return on Assets (ROA)  
 • Total Assets (end amount) is 14,890,758.71.  
 • ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100%  
  = (1,390,936.99 / 14,890,758.71) × 100% ≈ 9.34%

4. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
 • Accounts Receivable at the beginning is 0.00 and at the end is 3,149,338.94.  
 • The average Accounts Receivable = (0.00 + 3,149,338.94) / 2  
  = 1,574,669.47  
 • Main Business Revenue is used (assuming all sales are on credit) = 3,956,433.90  
 • Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio = Main Business Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable  
  = 3,956,433.90 / 1,574,669.47 ≈ 2.51

Thus, the final solution is:
